{"id":"2208.11143","submitter":"Kevin Shu","authors":"Kevin Shu","title":"Quadratic Programming with Sparsity Constraints via Polynomial Roots","comments":"The original version of this paper was replaced because we found a\n  substantially more efficient algorithm for the main result of this paper","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC math.AG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quadratically constrained quadratic programs (QCQPs) are an expressive family\nof optimization problems that occur naturally in many applications. It is often\nof interest to seek out sparse solutions, where many of the entries of the\nsolution are zero. This paper will consider QCQPs with a single linear\nconstraint, together with a sparsity constraint that requires that the set of\nnonzero entries of a solution be small. This problem class includes many\nfundamental problems of interest, such as sparse versions of linear regression\nand principal component analysis, which are both known to be very hard to\napproximate. We introduce a family of tractable approximations of such sparse\nQCQPs using the roots of polynomials which can be expressed as linear\ncombinations of principal minors of a matrix. These polynomials arose naturally\nfrom the study of hyperbolic polynomials. Our main contributions are\nformulations of these approximations and computational methods for finding good\nsolutions to a sparse QCQP. We will also give numerical evidence that these\nmethods can be effective on practical problems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 23 Aug 2022 18:07:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 29 Sep 2022 19:10:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-03"}
